</td><td><img src="/images/datel.gif" width=46 height=22 border=0><img src="/images/dateblnk.gif" width=100 height=22 border=0><img src="/images/dater.gif" width=306 height=22 border=0></td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td>
	


		<td valign=top width=452><table cellspacing="4" cellpadding="6" width=100% border=0><tr><td background="/images/newsback.gif"><CENTER><H3><FONT FACE="ARIAL" color="#CB723D">Dellan</FONT></H3></CENTER>
			
		<b>Level:</b> Pick One<br>

		<b>Race:</b> Dark Elf<br>

		<b>Class:</b> Wizard<br>

		<b>PvP Switch:</b>  Off<br>
		
		<center><h4>History:</h4></center>  After reciting a short incantation Dellan released the spell. As he felt the tingling energy<br>going through his entire body he saw small sparks appearing on the tips of his fingers. He<br>watched, fascinated with their gracious dance and the vivid glow they produced. Then<br>with a quick motion he straightened his arm and pointed at the rotting trunk of an old elm<br>tree. Immediately a rapidly growing bolt of fire rushed from his forefinger towards the<br>target. It was about ten inches in diameter when it made contact with the wrinkled surface<br>which gave away and exploded in a large cloud of smoke and splinters. <p>It was the second spell that he have learned since his arrival to Neriak, and the first<br>attempt of casting it. He felt drained, barely able to stand on his own, but he knew that it<br>would get better with time. All it takes is practice, and that he will have plenty in days to<br>come.<p>Suddenly he saw a dark face struck with deep lines of worry, but still beautiful and<br>somewhat familiar. Tired eyes were looking at him sadly, they were seeing into him,<br>scanning his soul for the foul thing he cherished throughout all these years. Vengeance. All<br>he lived for, all he cared for. It was the reason behind his return to the place that caused<br>him so much sorrow. He searched his memory, wanting to give the face a name but failing<br>to do so. The eyes, blue and deep like endless oceans, bore holes in his own. He lost the<br>track of time as he tried to escape the sorrow which haunted him for so long. The image<br>soon faltered and slowly died. But before that, recognition came.<p>"Mother!" he cried as he went down to his knees, his hands clutched at the ground ripping<br>it open. Tears were streaming from his eyes. Yes, he remembered. He always did, it was a<br>part of him he could never erase...<p>He saw himself in the cold apartments of father's study, standing in the middle of the room<br>facing a huge desk made of blackwood, surrounded by hundreds of bookshelves filled with<br>ancient texts. He could feel the power here, and with it a great unease. The gargoyle<br>statues positioned on the opposite sides of the great double doors, looked at him with<br>their empty stare, ready to come to life at their master's bidding.<p>Father was standing next to the large window in the back of the study, hands crossed on<br>his chest, following the flickering lights of the city with his cold gaze. He was clad in black<br>robes, so long that the soft fabric was trailing him smoothly when he walked, making him<br>appear as if he was floating in the very air. Dellan could see runes of protection woven<br>into the dark cloth, he could not recognize them, they were only readable to the highest<br>rank of necromancers.<p>"Do you know why are you here?" the dark-clad figure spoke without turning, his face<br>was still as if carved from stone, its sculptor restrained to give it any emotion. Only the<br>eyes seemed alive, shining with power and command. Also, there was madness, hidden<br>somewhere deep inside them, surfacing only in crucial moments, and those unfortunate to<br>look into them, rarely survived to tell about it.<p>"No master, I do not know why I was summoned," Dellan answered looking straight<br>ahead. It always was like this, cold and formal, even in the privacy of their house he was<br>forbidden to call this man father. Dellan hated him with every part of his being. Despised<br>him for what he did to mother and to her son. But above all he feared. And fear made him<br>a slave. <p>"You have become adept with the history of our kind, our land, and what I consider the<br>most important, you've learned the basics of mage-craft. You are ready to become my<br>apprentice." Slowly, father turned to face his son, "You will begin your studies<br>tomorrow." He eyed the small figure standing in the middle of the room, seeing just<br>another tool that would aid his evil plans. "Now go, say farewell to your mother. You will<br>not have time for her, or anyone else in that matter."<p>"But am I not too young for that?" his voice was only a whisper but the walls of the study<br>seemed to magnify it.<p>"You dare to question me," anger, and with it some of the hidden madness shone in<br>father's eyes. As he came closer, shadows revealed a cruel sneer on his face.<p>"No, never. All will be done according to your requests, master." He could not control the<br>shaking of hands anymore. As father neared him, he closed his eyes, awaiting punishment.<br>It did not come. Through his self created void he felt a hand touch his shoulder.<p>"I will let it pass, this one time only. Now go!" The hand tightened its grip. A piercing<br>cold shot through his arm, and with it pain. He withstood the urge to cry out, knowing<br>that it could only worsen his current situation. The whole thing lasted maybe two seconds,<br>but it seemed as if centuries have passed before the hand, and all the hurt that came with<br>it, went away.   <br>  	<br>Dellan bowed his head and turned to leave, resignation rooting itself into his heart, when<br>one of the doors opened and a slim figure entered the chambers. Her long hair were held<br>back by a platinum half-crown, a simple-cut spiderweb nightgown manifested her gentle<br>feminine curves, but all that was nothing compared to her enchanting beauty. She was<br>Ariisha of the a'Tal. She was destined to become a notable wizardess, but instead was<br>given to Belavid, the royal necromancer, so that their marriage could improve relations<br>between the house of a'Tal and the throne. She was gentle and caring, unlike most of the<br>Tier' Dal. She was his mother whom he dearly loved.<p>"What do you think you are doing Belavid?" her voice was strong as she spoke, her head<br>held high, she did not feel fear at this moment, concern for her only son washed it all<br>away. "I will not permit you to use my son for your foul purpose."<p>"You are forgetting yourself Ariisha. Besides he is also my son and my blood runs through<br>his veins." The cruel sneer appeared his face again and madness crept back into his eyes.<br>"I'm loosing my patience. Take him and bade him farewell, for it will be the last time you'll<br>see each other for quite some time." He waved his hand at mother and son, dismissing<br>them.<p>"No."  Ariisha shook her head vigorously. She suddenly knew that this was the time to<br>draw a line. This was the moment when she had to get away from this monster that once<br>have been her husband.  <br>	<br>At this point, Belavid's face lost its composure. His eyes were gleaming with pure madness<br>along with uncontrollable rage. He slapped Ariisha across the face making her stumble<br>backwards. A thin ripple of blood escaped the corner of her mouth and run down her chin.<br>She slowly brushed it away with the back of her hand. Looking up she saw straight into<br>the madman's eyes.<p>Dellan just stood there, watching as father gestured in the direction of mother at the same<br>time reciting three horrible words. Words that would bring an unimaginable pain. Ariisha<br>was caught in midair, trying desperately to jump away from harm's way. Too late. Air<br>escaped her lungs and she heard a snapping noise when her arm broke as it met the hard<br>surface of the wall. She started to fall, but four huge arms grabbed her, and held in an<br>upright position. The gargoyles, no more statues, looked to their creator, waiting for<br>orders.  <p>Another gesture, this one quicker, produced a twisted sacrificial blade in Belavid's right<br>hand. A wide, cruel smile was engraved on his face as he slowly strolled to the two<br>gargoyles and the figure suspended between them. Madness, hatred, and promise of an<br>eternal pain reflected in his eyes. It was impossible to look into them, withstand their<br>power or furthermore, to escape. The knife slowly rose, high above the wielder's head,<br>another hand came to rest on its hilt when it reached the desired position. And then it<br>came down...<p>A rain droplet splashed onto Dellan's forehead, cutting thoughts short, startling him.<br>Another ones followed the lead and soon enough he was soaking wet. He slowly got up<br>from the kneeling position and looked up into the starless sky. He gave his past another<br>brief moment, tried to muffle the mixed feelings of hate, pain and grief. It was hard, but he<br>was used to it by now, it was just another ritual in this miserable life. Slowly he started his<br>way back to the city. The city he would call home once more.     
<p><p>
		
